<subSubSection lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="52" pageId="12" pageNumber="51" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="12.[264,1323,1830,1897]" pageId="12" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,384,1830,1856]" pageId="12" pageNumber="51">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: The genus is easily recognized among Hawaiian dolichopodids by its conspicuously large tarsal claws (present in both males and females) combined with the long, thin,
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[264,1323,284,350]" pageId="13" pageNumber="52">
recurved and fused cerci of the hypopygium, and large unilobed surstyli without conspicuous setation (
<figureCitation box="[419,507,324,350]" captionStart="FIGURES 25–28" captionStartId="16.[264,382,1333,1357]" captionTargetBox="[313,1287,557,1313]" captionTargetId="figure-211@16.[289,1297,549,1324]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 25–28. Hypopygia. 25. Major minor (Parent). 26. Sigmatineurum napali Evenhuis. 27. Sweziella pictilipenna (Tenorio). 28. Uropachys flavicrurus (Hardy &amp; Kohn). Abbreviations: ae = aedeagus; av = apicoventral epandrial lobe; bv = basiventral epandrial lobe; hy = hypandrium; lh = lateral process of hypandrium; pg = postgonite; su = surstylus." pageId="13" pageNumber="52">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
